{"title_page": "Ernesto Sevilla", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{short description|Spanish screenwriter}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Ernesto Sevilla\n| image = Premios Goya 2018 - Ernesto Sevilla.jpg\n| caption = Ernesto Sevilla at [[32nd Goya Awards]]\n| birth_name = Ernesto Sevilla L\u00f3pez\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1978|05|16}}\n| birth_place = [[Albacete]]\n| height = {{height|m=1.77}}\n| father = Gabriel Sevilla\n| mother = Josefina L\u00f3pez\n| partner = {{plainlist|\n* [[Berta Collado]] (2010)\n* [[Patricia Conde]] (2015\u20132016)\n}}\n| alma_mater = [[Universidad de Castilla-La Mancha]]\n| occupation = TV director, actor, comedian, screenwriter and TV presenter\n}}\n\n'''Ernesto Sevilla L\u00f3pez''' (born 16 May 1978) is a Spanish TV director, actor, comedian, screenwriter and TV presenter.\n\n==Career==\nHe began as a screenwriter for [[Paramount Comedy (Spain)|Paramount Comedy]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latribunadeciudadreal.es/noticia/Z47006489-E5F6-9DA8-02E39CFF96F8F650/20141117/mucho/exito/no/teniamos |title=Mucho \u00e9xito no ten\u00edamos |first=M. |last=Sierra |date=17 November 2014 |access-date=7 October 2018 |work=La Tribuna de Ciudad Real |language=es}}</ref> In July 2015 he became a main character in ''[[La que se avecina]]'' with [[Jordi S\u00e1nchez (actor)|Jordi S\u00e1nchez]] and [[Nathalie Sese\u00f1a]].<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://teleprograma.diezminutos.es/series-tv/2015/julio/ernesto-sevilla-teodoro-la-que-se-avecina |title=Ernesto Sevilla se convierte en personaje fijo en \u2018La que se avecina\u2019 |first=Juan |last=Silvestre |date=15 July 2015 |access-date=22 November 2018 |magazine=[[Diez Minutos]] |language=es |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines International]]}}</ref> He appeared in an [[advertising campaign]] for Amena.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.comparatarifasmovil.es/blog/2017/07/anuncio-ernesto-sevilla-para-amena/ |title=Anuncio Ernesto Sevilla para Amena |date=22 July 2017 |access-date=12 September 2017 |work=Compara Tarifas M\u00f3vil |language=es}}</ref> In February 2018 he presented with [[Joaqu\u00edn Reyes (actor)|Joaqu\u00edn Reyes]] the [[32nd Goya Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.premiosgoya.com/32-edicion/articulos/ver/joaquin-reyes-ernesto-sevilla-premios-goya/ |title=Joaqu\u00edn Reyes y Ernesto Sevilla presentar\u00e1n los Goya |work=Premios Goya 2018 |access-date=18 December 2017 |language=es |date=14 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Premios Goya 2018: cu\u00e1ndo y d\u00f3nde ver la gala |url=https://elpais.com/cultura/2018/02/03/actualidad/1517651482_689227.html |date=3 February 2018 |access-date=13 April 2018 |newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |issn=1134-6582 |language=es |location=Madrid |publisher=[[Prisa]]}}</ref> He portrayed the TV series ''Cap\u00edtulo 0'' with Joaqu\u00edn Reyes, which was released on 11 September 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://vertele.eldiario.es/noticias/Capitulo-Joaquin-Ernesto-Sevilla-Movistar_0_2046695321.html |title=\"Cap\u00edtulo 0\", la serie de Joaqu\u00edn Reyes y Ernesto Sevilla, se estrena el 11 de septiembre en Movistar |date=6 September 2018 |access-date=22 November 2018 |newspaper=[[El Diario (Spain)|El Diario]] |publisher=Vertele! |language=es}}</ref> In April 2019 he will appeared in the film ''Lo dejo cuando quiera'', directed by Carlos Ther\u00f3n and starring [[Amaia Salamanca]], [[Cristina Casta\u00f1o]] and [[Miren Ibarguren]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telecinco.es/t5cinema/foto-oficial-dejo-quiera_0_2619225059.html |title=Ernesto Sevilla, Amaia Salamanca, Cristina Casta\u00f1o, Miren Ibarguren... As\u00ed posan ya en 'Lo dejo cuando quiera' |date=30 August 2018 |access-date=22 November 2018 |work=[[Telecinco]] |publisher=[[Mediaset Espa\u00f1a]] |language=es}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.fotogramas.es/noticias-cine/a22881734/lo-dejo-cuando-quiera-rodaje/ |title=Visita al rodaje de 'Lo dejo cuando quiera' |first=Mar\u00eda |last=Aller |date=31 August 2018 |access-date=22 November 2018 |magazine=Fotogramas |language=es |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines International]]}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFrom 2015 to 2016 he was in a relationship with the TV presenter [[Patricia Conde]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.divinity.es/parejas/claves-Ernesto-Sevilla-Patricia-Conde_0_2068500237.html |title=Diez claves sobre Ernesto Sevilla, el nuevo amor (con humor) de Patricia Conde |date=16 October 2015 |access-date=5 October 2018 |work=[[Divinity (TV channel)|Divinity]] |language=es |publisher=[[Mediaset Espa\u00f1a]]}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|1238859}}\n* {{Instagram|ernestosevillaoficial}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sevilla, Ernesto}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Castilian-Manchegan male actors]]\n[[Category:Spanish comedians]]\n[[Category:Spanish television presenters]]\n[[Category:Spanish television directors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Spanish male actors]]\n[[Category:Spanish directors]]\n[[Category:Spanish stand-up comedians]]\n[[Category:Spanish screenwriters]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{short description|Spanish screenwriter}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Ernesto Sevilla\n| image = Premios Goya 2018 - Ernesto Sevilla.jpg\n| caption = Ernesto Sevilla at [[32nd Goya Awards]]\n| birth_name = Ernesto Sevilla L\u00f3pez\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1978|05|16}}\n| birth_place = [[Albacete]]\n| height = {{height|m=1.77}}\n| father = Gabriel Sevilla\n| mother = Josefina L\u00f3pez\n| partner = {{plainlist|\n* [[Berta Collado]] (2010)\n* [[Patricia Conde]] (2015\u20132016)\n}}\n| alma_mater = [[Universidad de Castilla-La Mancha]]\n| occupation = TV director, actor, comedian, screenwriter and TV presenter\n}}\n\n'''Ernesto Sevilla L\u00f3pez''' (born 16 May 1978) is a Spanish TV director, actor, comedian, screenwriter and TV presenter.\n\n==Career==\nHe began as a screenwriter for [[Paramount Comedy (Spain)|Paramount Comedy]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latribunadeciudadreal.es/noticia/Z47006489-E5F6-9DA8-02E39CFF96F8F650/20141117/mucho/exito/no/teniamos |title=Mucho \u00e9xito no ten\u00edamos |first=M. |last=Sierra |date=17 November 2014 |access-date=7 October 2018 |work=La Tribuna de Ciudad Real |language=es}}</ref> In July 2015 he became a main character in ''[[La que se avecina]]'' with [[Jordi S\u00e1nchez]] and [[Nathalie Sese\u00f1a]].<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://teleprograma.diezminutos.es/series-tv/2015/julio/ernesto-sevilla-teodoro-la-que-se-avecina |title=Ernesto Sevilla se convierte en personaje fijo en \u2018La que se avecina\u2019 |first=Juan |last=Silvestre |date=15 July 2015 |access-date=22 November 2018 |magazine=[[Diez Minutos]] |language=es |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines International]]}}</ref> He appeared in an [[advertising campaign]] for Amena.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.comparatarifasmovil.es/blog/2017/07/anuncio-ernesto-sevilla-para-amena/ |title=Anuncio Ernesto Sevilla para Amena |date=22 July 2017 |access-date=12 September 2017 |work=Compara Tarifas M\u00f3vil |language=es}}</ref> In February 2018 he presented with [[Joaqu\u00edn Reyes (actor)|Joaqu\u00edn Reyes]] the [[32nd Goya Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.premiosgoya.com/32-edicion/articulos/ver/joaquin-reyes-ernesto-sevilla-premios-goya/ |title=Joaqu\u00edn Reyes y Ernesto Sevilla presentar\u00e1n los Goya |work=Premios Goya 2018 |access-date=18 December 2017 |language=es |date=14 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Premios Goya 2018: cu\u00e1ndo y d\u00f3nde ver la gala |url=https://elpais.com/cultura/2018/02/03/actualidad/1517651482_689227.html |date=3 February 2018 |access-date=13 April 2018 |newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |issn=1134-6582 |language=es |location=Madrid |publisher=[[Prisa]]}}</ref> He portrayed the TV series ''Cap\u00edtulo 0'' with Joaqu\u00edn Reyes, which was released on 11 September 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://vertele.eldiario.es/noticias/Capitulo-Joaquin-Ernesto-Sevilla-Movistar_0_2046695321.html |title=\"Cap\u00edtulo 0\", la serie de Joaqu\u00edn Reyes y Ernesto Sevilla, se estrena el 11 de septiembre en Movistar |date=6 September 2018 |access-date=22 November 2018 |newspaper=[[El Diario (Spain)|El Diario]] |publisher=Vertele! |language=es}}</ref> In April 2019 he will appeared in the film ''Lo dejo cuando quiera'', directed by Carlos Ther\u00f3n and starring [[Amaia Salamanca]], [[Cristina Casta\u00f1o]] and [[Miren Ibarguren]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telecinco.es/t5cinema/foto-oficial-dejo-quiera_0_2619225059.html |title=Ernesto Sevilla, Amaia Salamanca, Cristina Casta\u00f1o, Miren Ibarguren... As\u00ed posan ya en 'Lo dejo cuando quiera' |date=30 August 2018 |access-date=22 November 2018 |work=[[Telecinco]] |publisher=[[Mediaset Espa\u00f1a]] |language=es}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.fotogramas.es/noticias-cine/a22881734/lo-dejo-cuando-quiera-rodaje/ |title=Visita al rodaje de 'Lo dejo cuando quiera' |first=Mar\u00eda |last=Aller |date=31 August 2018 |access-date=22 November 2018 |magazine=Fotogramas |language=es |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines International]]}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFrom 2015 to 2016 he was in a relationship with the TV presenter [[Patricia Conde]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.divinity.es/parejas/claves-Ernesto-Sevilla-Patricia-Conde_0_2068500237.html |title=Diez claves sobre Ernesto Sevilla, el nuevo amor (con humor) de Patricia Conde |date=16 October 2015 |access-date=5 October 2018 |work=[[Divinity (TV channel)|Divinity]] |language=es |publisher=[[Mediaset Espa\u00f1a]]}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|1238859}}\n* {{Instagram|ernestosevillaoficial}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sevilla, Ernesto}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Castilian-Manchegan male actors]]\n[[Category:Spanish comedians]]\n[[Category:Spanish television presenters]]\n[[Category:Spanish television directors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Spanish male actors]]\n[[Category:Spanish directors]]\n[[Category:Spanish stand-up comedians]]\n[[Category:Spanish screenwriters]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toJordi S\u00e1nchez(link changed toJordi S\u00e1nchez (actor)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ernesto_Sevilla"}
{"title_page": "The Blanket of the Dark", "text_new": "{{short description|1931 novel by John Buchan}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2018}}\n{{infobox book \n| name         = The Blanket of the Dark\n| author       = [[John Buchan, 1st Baron Tweedsmuir|John Buchan]]\n| language     = English\n| country      = England\n| genre        = Novel\n| publisher    = [[Hodder & Stoughton]]<ref name=\"BLcat\">{{Cite web |url=http://primocat.bl.uk/F?func=direct&local_base=ITEMV&doc_number=000512612&con_lng=eng |title=British Library Item details |website=primocat.bl.uk|access-date=2018-01-07}}</ref>\n| orig title   =\n| translator   =\n| image        = File:The_Blanket_of_the_Dark_by_John_Buchan,_first_edition_cover.jpg\n| border       =\n| caption      =\n| cover_artist = \n| release_date = 1931<ref name=\"BLcat\"/>\n| media_type   = Print\n| pages        = 314<ref name=\"BLcat\"/>\n}}\n'''''The Blanket of the Dark''''' is a 1931 historical novel by the Scottish author [[John Buchan]]. The novel is set in the early part of the reign of [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]], and explores the possible consequences had the [[Tudor Dynasty|Tudors]] been overthrown by a rightful descendant of [[Edward III of England|Edward III]].<ref name=\"Daniell185\">{{Cite book|last=Daniell|first=David|title=The Interpreter's House|publisher=Thomas Nelson and Sons Ltd|year=1975|isbn=0 17 146051 0|page=185}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThe action of the novel takes place in the country west of [[Oxford]] during the 1536 [[Pilgrimage of Grace]], an uprising against Henry VIII. Peter Pentecost, a young monastic scholar, is informed by shadowy figures who are plotting to depose the king that he is the legitimate son of the [[Edward Stafford, 3rd Duke of Buckingham|Duke of Buckingham]] and that, as the last of the [[Bohun family|Bohun line]], he has a claim to the English throne.\n\nAlthough his true identity must for now remain secret, Peter soon finds himself being prepared for his intended kingly role and being tutored in the noble pursuits of [[swordsmanship]] and [[archery]]. He meets a noblewoman, Sabine Beauforest.\n\nTo hide from the king\u2019s men, Peter takes to the greenwood where he is aided by Solomon Darking and his vagabond comrades. They introduce him to the lore of the countryside, and reveal the existence of an entirely self-contained outlaw society, invisible to the agents of the state, with its own system of communication and intelligence gathering. He discovers that \u2018under the blanket of the dark all men are alike and all are nameless'.\n\nAs the novel progresses, Peter realises he is having increasing doubts about of the venture he is being asked to undertake, and the motives of those behind it: \u201cThey claimed to stand for the elder England and its rights, and [[Catholic Church|the old Church]], but at their heart they stood only for themselves.\u201d After an encounter with the King himself, Peter asks himself whether there \u201cmight not there be a world of light under the blanket of the dark?\u201d, and he decides that he does not wish to pursue a life of power. He disappears from official sight back into the greenwood with Sabine.\n\n== Critical reception==\n\n[[David Daniell (author)|David Daniell]] in ''The Interpreter's House'' (1975) quotes [[Rudyard Kipling|Kipling]] who professed to be \"rested and delighted\" by the book and who called it a tour de force. [[Rose Macaulay]] said that the book was \"so enchanting and beautiful that I often read it for my pleasure\". Daniell himself notes that while the tone is relaxed, the control is tight, and \"it is as if Buchan is drawing together all his skills under the influence of his response to the land and its people\".<ref name=\"Daniell185\"/>\n\nWriting for the ''John Buchan Society'' website in 2001, Kenneth Hillier called ''The Blanket of the Dark'' \u201ca thoroughly enjoyable book, because it not only expresses the deep love Buchan had for his adopted countryside but it conveys great empathy with the period in which it is set\u201d.<ref name=\"John Buchan Society website\">{{cite web | url=http://www.johnbuchansociety.co.uk/books/82.htm | title=John Buchan Society website | accessdate=10 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nDavid Goldie noted in 2009 that \"One of the animating ideas of ''The Blanket of the Dark'' is that English values are expressed more profoundly in the quiet wisdom of its folk than in the forceful actions of its rulers\".<ref name=\"Goldie\">{{cite book |last=Goldie |first=David |editor-first=Kate |editor-last=Macdonald |chapter=Twin Loyalties: John Buchan\u2019s England | p = 34 |title=Reassessing John Buchan: beyond the Third-Nine Steps |publisher=[[Pickering & Chatto Publishers|Pickering & Chatto]] |publication-place=London |year=2009 |isbn=978-1851969982}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the historian [[Diarmaid MacCulloch]] called it a \"wonderful young adult book\", also describing it as \"chilling\" and \"brilliant\".<ref name=\"Preston\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2019/jul/13/diarmaid-maculloch-thomas-cromwell-a-life-interview-hilary-mantel |title=Diarmaid MacCulloch: \u2018I got very irritated with Henry VIII\u2019  |last=Preston |first=Alex |date=13 July 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=18 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{FadedPage|id=20120404|name=The Blanket of the Dark}}\n*[http://gutenberg.net.au/ebooks03/0301411h.html ''The Blanket of the Dark''] at [[Project Gutenberg]]\n\n{{John Buchan}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blanket Of The Dark}}\n[[Category:Novels by John Buchan]]\n[[Category:1931 British novels]]\n[[Category:Hodder & Stoughton books]]\n[[Category:British historical novels]]\n[[Category:British alternative history novels]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1931 novel by John Buchan}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2018}}\n{{infobox book \n| name         = The Blanket of the Dark\n| author       = [[John Buchan, 1st Baron Tweedsmuir|John Buchan]]\n| language     = English\n| country      = England\n| genre        = Novel\n| publisher    = [[Hodder & Stoughton]]<ref name=\"BLcat\">{{Cite web |url=http://primocat.bl.uk/F?func=direct&local_base=ITEMV&doc_number=000512612&con_lng=eng |title=British Library Item details |website=primocat.bl.uk|access-date=2018-01-07}}</ref>\n| orig title   =\n| translator   =\n| image        = File:The_Blanket_of_the_Dark_by_John_Buchan,_first_edition_cover.jpg\n| border       =\n| caption      =\n| cover_artist = \n| release_date = 1931<ref name=\"BLcat\"/>\n| media_type   = Print\n| pages        = 314<ref name=\"BLcat\"/>\n}}\n'''''The Blanket of the Dark''''' is a 1931 historical novel by the Scottish author [[John Buchan]]. The novel is set in the early part of the reign of [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]], and explores the possible consequences had the [[Tudor Dynasty|Tudors]] been overthrown by a rightful descendant of [[Edward III of England|Edward III]].<ref name=\"Daniell185\">{{Cite book|last=Daniell|first=David|title=The Interpreter's House|publisher=Thomas Nelson and Sons Ltd|year=1975|isbn=0 17 146051 0|page=185}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThe action of the novel takes place in the country west of Oxford during the 1536 [[Pilgrimage of Grace]], an uprising against Henry VIII. Peter Pentecost, a young monastic scholar, is informed by shadowy figures who are plotting to depose the king that he is the legitimate son of the [[Edward Stafford, 3rd Duke of Buckingham|Duke of Buckingham]] and that, as the last of the [[Bohun family|Bohun line]], he has a claim to the English throne.\n\nAlthough his true identity must for now remain secret, Peter soon finds himself being prepared for his intended kingly role and being tutored in the noble pursuits of swordmanship and archery. He meets a noblewoman, Sabine Beauforest.\n\nTo hide from the king\u2019s men, Peter takes to the greenwood where he is aided by Solomon Darking and his vagabond comrades. They introduce him to the lore of the countryside, and reveal the existence of an entirely self-contained outlaw society, invisible to the agents of the state, with its own system of communication and intelligence gathering. He discovers that \u2018under the blanket of the dark all men are alike and all are nameless'.\n\nAs the novel progresses, Peter realises he is having increasing doubts about of the venture he is being asked to undertake, and the motives of those behind it: \u201cThey claimed to stand for the elder England and its rights, and the old Church, but at their heart they stood only for themselves.\u201d After an encounter with the King himself, Peter asks himself whether there \u201cmight not there be a world of light under the blanket of the dark?\u201d, and he decides that he does not wish to pursue a life of power. He disappears from official sight back into the greenwood with Sabine.\n\n== Critical reception==\n\n[[David Daniell (author)|David Daniell]] in ''The Interpreter's House'' (1975) quotes [[Rudyard Kipling|Kipling]] who professed to be \"rested and delighted\" by the book and who called it a tour de force. [[Rose Macaulay]] said that the book was \"so enchanting and beautiful that I often read it for my pleasure\". Daniell himself notes that while the tone is relaxed, the control is tight, and \"it is as if Buchan is drawing together all his skills under the influence of his response to the land and its people\".<ref name=\"Daniell185\"/>\n\nWriting for the ''John Buchan Society'' website in 2001, Kenneth Hillier called ''The Blanket of the Dark'' \u201ca thoroughly enjoyable book, because it not only expresses the deep love Buchan had for his adopted countryside but it conveys great empathy with the period in which it is set\u201d.<ref name=\"John Buchan Society website\">{{cite web | url=http://www.johnbuchansociety.co.uk/books/82.htm | title=John Buchan Society website | accessdate=10 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nDavid Goldie noted in 2009 that \"One of the animating ideas of ''The Blanket of the Dark'' is that English values are expressed more profoundly in the quiet wisdom of its folk than in the forceful actions of its rulers\".<ref name=\"Goldie\">{{cite book |last=Goldie |first=David |editor-first=Kate |editor-last=Macdonald |chapter=Twin Loyalties: John Buchan\u2019s England | p = 34 |title=Reassessing John Buchan: beyond the Third-Nine Steps |publisher=[[Pickering & Chatto Publishers|Pickering & Chatto]] |publication-place=London |year=2009 |isbn=978-1851969982}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the historian [[Diarmaid MacCulloch]] called it a \"wonderful young adult book\", also describing it as \"chilling\" and \"brilliant\".<ref name=\"Preston\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2019/jul/13/diarmaid-maculloch-thomas-cromwell-a-life-interview-hilary-mantel |title=Diarmaid MacCulloch: \u2018I got very irritated with Henry VIII\u2019  |last=Preston |first=Alex |date=13 July 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=18 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{FadedPage|id=20120404|name=The Blanket of the Dark}}\n*[http://gutenberg.net.au/ebooks03/0301411h.html ''The Blanket of the Dark''] at [[Project Gutenberg]]\n\n{{John Buchan}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blanket Of The Dark}}\n[[Category:Novels by John Buchan]]\n[[Category:1931 British novels]]\n[[Category:Hodder & Stoughton books]]\n[[Category:British historical novels]]\n[[Category:British alternative history novels]]\n", "name_user": "MichaelMaggs", "label": "safe", "comment": "+links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Blanket_of_the_Dark"}
